Characterization of White Matter and Cerebrospinal Fluid Biomarker Associations in Alzheimerâ€™s Disease

Nik Padmanabhan

Overview

This project aims to find associations between white matter content and CSF biomarker levels in Alzheimerâ€™s patients, using Alzheimerâ€™s Disease neuroimaging initiative (ADNI) data. Although Alzheimerâ€™s disease primarily affects grey matter, results of this work could improve early characterization of the disease. This project would not have been possible without Choonsik Leeâ€™s recommendations for dicom image visualization, Taki Shinoharaâ€™s help with FSLR, and Konrad Kordingâ€™s recommendations of machine learning approaches. A link to my GitHub repository is included:

https://github.com/nikpad/BMIN503_Final_Project

Introduction

Alzheimerâ€™s disease, which is a progressive, chronic, neurodegenerative disease, currently affects almost 6 million Americans. There is currently no cure or method to stop its progression. After diagnosis, the life expectancy of patients generally ranges from 3-10 years. The disease, characterized by extracellular amyloid beta deposits and neurofibrillary tangles, primarily affects grey matter in the brain. However, white matter abnormalities also exist, although these changes take place prior to the neurodegenerative process. Patients with preclinical Alzheimerâ€™s disease, before substantial changes of the grey matter have happened, have been shown to have similar levels of white matter abnormalities as patients in later stages. These abnormalities generally include myelin and oligodendrocyte loss. Assiciations between white matter content and cerebrospinal fluid biomarkers, such as amyloid beta and tau proteins, could improve the understanding of the pathogenesis of Alzheimerâ€™s disease, which could improve and expedite the development of treatments.

This analysis was facilitated by the ADNI, in which multiple types of data, including clinical, imaging, and biospecimen data, were collected from both affected and control populations. The imaging data must be treated differently than the other data types, as quantitative values were first extracted for comparison. The R packages oro.dicom and oro.nifti enable analyzing MRI data, for processes such as visualization and segmentation. In this work, segmentation based on overall pixel intensities was used to estimate white matter content. In addition, toolkits in R such as ANTs and FSL enable image preprocessing procedures such as image registration, brain extraction, and inhomogeneity correction. Once numerical values have been extracted from the image data, statistical models can be developed to better understand the characteristics Alzheimerâ€™s disease. An end goal of this work would be for supervised machine learning algrithms to be able to predict disease progression of patients in early stages. This work will hopefully impact the understanding of the disease over time, and therefore improve the development of treatments.

Methods

Project data included both biomarker and T2 weighted MRI images for 60 patients. Biomarker data included both baseline and 12 month data for amyloid beta, tau, and p-tau. Of the 60 patients, 30 were from a cognitively normal (CN) group, and 30 were from an Alzheimerâ€™s Disease (AD) group. For MRI data, individual dicom files were converted to a nifti file for easier manipulation. Afterwards, the imagesâ€™ intensities were transformed to improve visualization. Brain extraction was carried out with FSLR, and image segmentation was carried out based on each imageâ€™s intensity histogram to estimate white matter content. A representative process is shown in this section, and this process is completed for the rest of the 60 patients in the results section. Hierarchical clustering and random forests were used to compare biomarker, white matter content, and their combinationâ€™s ability to cluster and predict cognitive state. Additionally, baseline and 12 month data were compared to assess disease progression.

#Define a different transfer function
lin.sp<-function(x,knots,slope){
    knots<-c(min(x),knots,max(x))
    slopeS<-slope[1]
 for(j in 2:length(slope)){
   slopeS<-c(slopeS,slope[j]-sum(slopeS))}
   rvals<-numeric(length(x))
 for(i in 2:length(knots)){
   rvals<-ifelse(x>=knots[i-1], slopeS[i-1]*(x-knots[i-1])+rvals,rvals)}
 return(rvals)}
#Define a spline with three knots and four slopes
knot.vals<-c(.25,.5,.74)
slp.vals<-c(2,1,.5,.25)
#knot.vals<-c(0.5)
#slp.vals<-c(1,1)


#Plot the Spline Transfer Function
par(new = TRUE)
curve(lin.sp(x,knot.vals,slp.vals),axes=FALSE,xlab="",ylab="",col=2,lwd=3)
axis(side=4,at = pretty(range(im_hist$mids))/max(nii),labels=pretty(range(im_hist$mids)))
mtext("Transformed Intensity", side=4, line=2) 

trans<-lin.sp(nii, knot.vals*max(nii), slp.vals)
image(nii,z=36,plot.type='single', main="Original Image")

image(trans,z=36,plot.type='single',main="Transformed Image") 

#Original Image Histogram
s2 <- nii[,,36]
hist(s2[s2>0],breaks=100, xlab="Intensities", prob=T, col=rgb(0,0,1,1/4), main="")

#Transformed Image Histogram
s3 <- trans[,,36]
hist(s3[s3>0],breaks=100, xlab="Intensities", prob=T, col=rgb(0,0,1,1/4), main="")

  filter(cognitive_state=="CN")

## [1] 75.00333

While the mean age between AD and CN patients were very similar, the overall distributions were more variable. This is most likely due to a small sample size of 30 patients in each group.

White Matter Content:

ggplot(data=data_bl, aes(x=cognitive_state, y=white_matter_ratio)) +
    ggtitle("White Matter Content")+
    geom_boxplot()

While there is a noticable difference between AD and CN groups for the segmented white matter content, there is also a substantial overlap of the data. As a result, white matter content, if it does take place before grey matter degeneration, is not sufficient to fully predict Alzheimerâ€™s Disease.

BL Logistic Regression Bivariate Analysis:

#Logistic regression, due to predicting a binary outcome from a set of continuous predictor variables
n.var <- 4
pvals <- as.list(rep(NA, n.var))
names(pvals) <- c("white_matter_ratio","ABETA","TAU","PTAU")
for (i in 1:n.var){
    glm.out <- glm(data_bl$cognitive_state ~ data_bl[[i+5]], family=binomial("logit"))
    curr.p <- coef(summary(glm.out))[,4][2]
    pvals[i] <- curr.p
}

imp <- rf$importance
#MeanDecreaseGini
head(sort(imp[,4], decreasing=TRUE), n=20)
##              ABETA               PTAU                TAU white_matter_ratio 
##          11.252526           7.615802           6.351251           4.308420
rf.pred <- predict(rf, data_bl, type="prob")

N = nrow(data_bl)
K = 10
set.seed(1234)
s = sample(1:K, size=N, replace=T)
pred_outputs.rf <- vector(mode="numeric", length=N)
obs_outputs <- vector(mode="numeric", length=N)
offset <- 0
for(i in 1:K){
    train <- filter(data_bl, s != i)
    test <- filter(data_bl, s == i)
    obs_outputs[1:length(s[s==i]) + offset] <- test$cognitive_state

    #RF train/test
    rf <- randomForest(cognitive_state~white_matter_ratio + ABETA + TAU + PTAU, data=train, ntree=100)
    rf.pred.curr <- predict(rf, newdata=test, type="prob") 
    pred_outputs.rf[1:length(s[s==i]) + offset] <- rf.pred.curr[,2]

    offset <- offset + length(s[s==i])
}

#ROC curves - one plot of the four tests
library(pROC)
## Type 'citation("pROC")' for a citation.
## 
## Attaching package: 'pROC'

##     cov, smooth, var

## Warning in ci.auc.roc(roc, ...): ci.auc() of a ROC curve with AUC == 1 is always 1-1 and can be misleading.
plot.roc(obs_outputs, pred_outputs.rf, ci=TRUE, col="red", add=TRUE) 
legend("bottomright", legend=c("RF Training", "RF Cross-Validation"), col=c("darkgreen", "red"), lwd=2)

auc(data_bl$cognitive_state, rf.pred[, 2])
## Area under the curve: 1
auc(obs_outputs, pred_outputs.rf)
## Area under the curve: 0.945

According to the gini importance scores, ABETA is the most important biomarker predictor.

Conclusions

Overall, white matter content ratio calculation was successful after transformation, brain extraction, and segmentation. However, the process required estimation, and is not perfectly reproducible. Even though transforming the data helped to isolate the white matter peak in the intensity histogram, the start and end intensities were chosen based on imperfect estimation. This segmentation process could be compared with segmentation using advanced normalization tools (ANTs), to assess its accuracy. White matter content displayed a significant difference between AD and CN groups after logistic regression bivariate analysis, although there was substantial overlap in the groups. This will make it difficult to predict potential future grey matter degredation using only white matter content. In terms of biomarker data, both baseline and 12 month data showed amyloid beta, tau, and p-tau biomarkers were associated with cognitive state at a significance level of 0.05. However, the difference between 12 month and baseline data was not significant. This engendered the question of whether there was any disease progression at all between baseline and 12 month timepoints. Using hierarchical clustering and random forests, both clustering and cross-validation prediction improved from baseline to 12 month timepoints, showing that there was some degree of disease progression. In addition, hierarchical clustering was used to assess white matter content. Biomarker data performed much better than white matter content in clustering, although white matter addition to biomarker data did not improve or reduce clustering accuracy for both baseline and 12 month data. A better form of characterization could be White matter integrity visualization using diffusion tensor imaging. This could determine how white matter is initially affected, as opposed to how much is affected.
